) RETURNING id INTO v_mod2;

-- Module 2 Lessons
INSERT INTO course_lessons (id, module_id, title, content, sort_order) VALUES
('ui-2-1', v_mod2, 'How Tenancy in Common Works', E'# How Tenancy in Common Works\n\nTenancy in common (TIC) is the most common and most flexible form of shared ownership. Understanding its mechanics is essential for every real estate agent.\n\n## Creation\n\nA tenancy in common is created whenever two or more people take title to property together **without specifying** joint tenancy or another form. It is the **default** form of co-ownership in most states.\n\nThe deed might read:\n> \"To Alice Smith and Bob Jones, as tenants in common.\"\n\nOr simply:\n> \"To Alice Smith and Bob Jones.\"\n\nBoth typically create a tenancy in common (check your state law, as a few states still default to joint tenancy).\n\n## Ownership Shares\n\nOne of the key advantages of TIC is that owners can hold **unequal shares**:\n\n- Two owners: 50/50, 60/40, 70/30, or any split\n- Three or more owners: any combination that totals 100%\n- Shares are usually stated on the deed or in a separate TIC agreement\n\nIf the deed does not specify shares, most states presume **equal ownership** regardless of how much each person contributed to the purchase price.\n\n**Agent tip:** Always ensure the deed clearly states each owner''s percentage interest. This prevents disputes down the road.\n\n## Rights of TIC Owners\n\nEach tenant in common has the right to:\n\n1. **Possess and use** the entire property (not just \"their share\")\n2. **Receive their proportional share** of rental income or profits\n3. **Sell, transfer, or mortgage** their individual interest without consent from other owners\n4. **Will their share** to any beneficiary — there is no right of survivorship\n5. **File a partition action** to force division or sale of the property\n\n## Obligations of TIC Owners\n\nCo-owners are also expected to:\n\n- Pay their **proportional share** of property taxes, insurance, and maintenance\n- Not commit **waste** (actions that damage or reduce the property''s value)\n- **Account to other owners** for profits received from the property\n- Not **exclude** other co-owners from the property\n\n## What Happens Without a TIC Agreement?\n\nWhen co-owners take title without a written agreement, disputes often arise over:\n\n- Who pays for repairs and improvements?\n- Can one owner rent out the property (or part of it) without consent?\n- What if one owner wants to sell and the others don''t?\n- How are expenses shared if ownership is unequal?\n\nA well-drafted **TIC agreement** (also called a co-ownership agreement) addresses all of these issues in advance. As an agent, encouraging your clients to get a TIC agreement is one of the most valuable pieces of advice you can give.\n\n## Summary\n\nTenancy in common offers maximum flexibility in co-ownership but also requires clear communication and documentation. Without a proper TIC agreement, even the simplest arrangements can become complicated disputes.', 1),

('ui-2-2', v_mod2, 'TIC Agreements: What Every Agent Should Know', E'# TIC Agreements: What Every Agent Should Know\n\nA **Tenancy in Common (TIC) Agreement** is a private contract between co-owners that sets the ground rules for their shared ownership. While not required by law, it is arguably the most important document in any co-ownership arrangement.\n\n## Why TIC Agreements Matter\n\nWithout a TIC agreement, co-owners must rely on **default state law**, which often leads to:\n- Expensive litigation to resolve disputes\n- Partition actions that force a sale at below-market prices\n- Confusion about who is responsible for which expenses\n- Inability to get financing (lenders often require TIC agreements)\n\n## Key Provisions to Include\n\n### 1. Ownership Percentages\nClearly state each owner''s percentage interest and how it was determined (e.g., based on capital contributions).\n\n### 2. Financial Obligations\n- How mortgage payments are split\n- Who pays property taxes, insurance, HOA fees\n- How maintenance and repair costs are shared\n- What happens if one owner fails to pay their share\n\n### 3. Use and Occupancy\n- Who can occupy the property and when\n- Rules about exclusive use of certain areas\n- Limitations on guests, subletting, or short-term rentals\n- Rules about pets, smoking, noise, and alterations\n\n### 4. Decision-Making\n- What decisions require unanimous consent (e.g., major renovations)\n- What decisions can be made by majority vote\n- How disputes are resolved (mediation, arbitration, or litigation)\n\n### 5. Transfer Restrictions\n- **Right of first refusal** — other owners get the chance to buy before a share is sold to an outsider\n- Notice requirements before selling\n- Restrictions on who a share can be sold or transferred to\n- How a departing owner''s share is valued\n\n### 6. Buyout and Exit Provisions\n- How an owner can exit the arrangement\n- Buyout valuation method (appraisal, formula, negotiation)\n- Payment terms for a buyout\n- What triggers a forced sale (deadlock, default, bankruptcy)\n\n### 7. Death and Incapacity\n- What happens to an owner''s share when they die\n- Requirements for estate planning (e.g., must include property in will or trust)\n- Rights of heirs to participate in or opt out of the TIC\n\n### 8. Insurance and Liability\n- Minimum insurance coverage requirements\n- How liability is shared if someone is injured on the property\n- Requirements for umbrella or liability policies\n\n## Financing Considerations\n\nTIC arrangements present unique financing challenges:\n\n- Most lenders prefer a **single mortgage** on the entire property, making all owners jointly liable\n- In some markets (notably San Francisco), **fractional TIC loans** are available where each owner gets their own mortgage on their share\n- If one owner defaults on a shared mortgage, **all owners** are at risk of foreclosure\n- Some lenders require a TIC agreement as a condition of the loan\n\n## The Agent''s Role\n\nAs an agent, you should:\n\n1. **Ask clients** if they have a TIC agreement whenever you list or show a TIC property\n2. **Recommend** that buyers entering a TIC arrangement hire an attorney to draft a TIC agreement\n3. **Understand the basics** so you can identify potential issues\n4. **Never draft** a TIC agreement yourself — this is the practice of law\n\n## Summary\n\nA TIC agreement is the foundation of a successful co-ownership arrangement. Agents who understand what these agreements contain and why they matter can provide significantly better guidance to clients involved in shared ownership transactions.', 2),

('ui-2-3', v_mod2, 'Real-World TIC Scenarios for Agents', E'# Real-World TIC Scenarios for Agents\n\nLet''s walk through common scenarios you''ll encounter as an agent dealing with tenancy in common properties. These real-world examples will help you identify issues and advise your clients effectively.\n\n## Scenario 1: The Inherited Property\n\n**Situation:** Three siblings inherit their parents'' home as tenants in common (one-third each). One sibling wants to sell, one wants to keep it as a rental, and one wants to live in it.\n\n**Key Issues:**\n- No single owner can force the others to agree on a use\n- The sibling who wants to sell can file a **partition action** to force a sale\n- The sibling living in the home may owe **fair rental value** to the others\n- If the home has an existing mortgage, who is responsible for payments?\n\n**Agent''s Role:**\n- Help the siblings understand their options: buyout, sell, or agree on a use\n- If listing the property, ensure **all owners sign the listing agreement**\n- Recommend mediation if the siblings disagree\n- Refer to an attorney if a partition action seems likely\n\n## Scenario 2: Unmarried Couple Buying Together\n\n**Situation:** An unmarried couple wants to buy a home together. They''re splitting the down payment 70/30 because one partner has more savings.\n\n**Key Issues:**\n- Without specifying ownership shares, the state may presume 50/50\n- If they break up, there''s no divorce court to divide the property\n- A TIC agreement is **essential** to protect both parties\n- They need to decide: what happens if one person wants to move out?\n\n**Agent''s Role:**\n- Advise them to get a TIC agreement before closing\n- Ensure the deed reflects the agreed-upon ownership percentages\n- Discuss what happens in a breakup scenario (uncomfortable but necessary)\n- Recommend they each consult their own attorney\n\n## Scenario 3: Investment Group Purchase\n\n**Situation:** Four friends want to buy a vacation rental together, each contributing 25% of the purchase price.\n\n**Key Issues:**\n- Who manages the property and bookings?\n- How is rental income distributed?\n- What if one investor wants out after two years?\n- Insurance, tax, and liability considerations\n\n**Agent''s Role:**\n- Recommend they form an **LLC** instead of holding title as individuals (better liability protection)\n- If they insist on TIC, strongly recommend a detailed TIC agreement\n- Help them understand the financing implications (investment property rates, each person''s DTI affected)\n- Advise on short-term rental regulations in the area\n\n## Scenario 4: The Reluctant Seller\n\n**Situation:** You''re listing a property where one of two TIC owners wants to sell but the other refuses.\n\n**Key Issues:**\n- You **cannot list the entire property** with only one owner''s consent\n- The willing seller can list **only their undivided interest** — but these are extremely hard to sell\n- The willing seller''s main leverage is threatening a partition action\n- A partition sale often results in a below-market price\n\n**Agent''s Role:**\n- Explain the realities of selling an undivided interest on the open market\n- Suggest negotiation or mediation first\n- Refer to a real estate attorney experienced in partition actions\n- If listing the partial interest, disclose the co-ownership situation clearly\n\n## Scenario 5: The 1031 Exchange Complication\n\n**Situation:** Three TIC investors want to sell their investment property and do a 1031 exchange, but one investor wants to cash out.\n\n**Key Issues:**\n- All three must agree to sell (or force a partition)\n- The two continuing investors need the sale structured as a 1031 exchange\n- The cashing-out investor will owe capital gains tax\n- Timing is critical — 1031 exchanges have strict deadlines\n\n**Agent''s Role:**\n- Coordinate with a qualified intermediary for the 1031 exchange\n- Ensure the purchase agreement accommodates the exchange\n- Help the cashing-out investor understand the tax implications\n- Work with a CPA and attorney to structure the transaction correctly\n\n## Key Takeaways for Agents\n\n1. **Always ask about co-ownership details** at the beginning of any transaction involving multiple owners\n2. **Never assume** all owners are on the same page\n3. **Get signatures from ALL owners** on listing agreements and purchase contracts\n4. **Recommend professional help** — attorneys, mediators, CPAs — early and often\n5. **Document everything** in writing to protect yourself and your clients\n\n## Summary\n\nTIC properties present unique challenges, but they also represent opportunities for agents who know how to navigate them. The key is identifying issues early, communicating clearly with all parties, and knowing when to bring in specialized professionals.', 3);

