-- =============================================
-- MODULE 3: Joint Tenancy and Survivorship
-- =============================================
INSERT INTO course_modules (title, section, description, tier, sort_order, course_id)
VALUES (
  'Joint Tenancy and Survivorship',
  'Understanding Shared Ownership',
  'Master the mechanics of joint tenancy, the right of survivorship, how joint tenancies are created and severed, and the critical implications for your clients.',
  'free',
  3,
  v_course_id
) RETURNING id INTO v_mod3;

INSERT INTO course_lessons (id, module_id, title, content, sort_order) VALUES
('ui-3-1', v_mod3, 'Creating and Maintaining a Joint Tenancy', E'# Creating and Maintaining a Joint Tenancy\n\nJoint tenancy is a form of co-ownership defined by one powerful feature: the **right of survivorship**. When one joint tenant dies, their share automatically transfers to the surviving joint tenant(s) — no probate required.\n\n## The Four Unities\n\nTo create a valid joint tenancy, four conditions (the \"four unities\") must be met simultaneously:\n\n### 1. Unity of Time\nAll joint tenants must acquire their interest at the **same time**. You cannot add a new joint tenant to an existing ownership — doing so breaks the joint tenancy.\n\n### 2. Unity of Title\nAll joint tenants must acquire their interest through the **same deed or document**. Two people who acquire interests in the same property through separate deeds cannot be joint tenants.\n\n### 3. Unity of Interest\nAll joint tenants must hold **equal shares**. If two people own a property as joint tenants, they each own exactly 50%. Three joint tenants each own exactly one-third. There is no such thing as an unequal joint tenancy.\n\n### 4. Unity of Possession\nAll joint tenants have an **equal right to possess** the entire property. No joint tenant can claim exclusive use of any particular portion.\n\n## Explicit Intent Required\n\nIn most states, the deed must **expressly state** that the owners hold title as joint tenants:\n\n> \"To Alice Smith and Bob Jones, as joint tenants with right of survivorship, and not as tenants in common.\"\n\nSome states require the phrase \"with right of survivorship\" or similar language. Without it, the ownership defaults to tenancy in common.\n\n## The Right of Survivorship in Action\n\nHere''s how the right of survivorship works in practice:\n\n**Example:** Alice and Bob own a home as joint tenants (50/50). Alice passes away.\n\n1. Alice''s 50% interest **automatically** transfers to Bob\n2. Bob now owns 100% of the property\n3. Alice''s heirs receive **nothing** from this property — regardless of what Alice''s will says\n4. No probate is needed for the transfer\n5. Bob typically just needs to record a death certificate and an affidavit of survivorship\n\nThis is one of the main reasons people choose joint tenancy — it provides a simple, inexpensive way to transfer property at death.\n\n## Common Uses of Joint Tenancy\n\n- **Married couples** who want the surviving spouse to automatically inherit\n- **Parents and adult children** for estate planning (though this has tax implications)\n- **Business partners** who want the surviving partner to continue ownership\n\n## Potential Pitfalls\n\n- Cannot leave your share to anyone other than the surviving joint tenant(s)\n- Gift tax implications when adding someone to the deed\n- Loss of the stepped-up tax basis on the deceased owner''s share (in some cases)\n- Creditors of one joint tenant may be able to force a sale in some states\n- Medicaid eligibility can be affected\n\n## Summary\n\nJoint tenancy is a powerful estate planning and ownership tool, but it must be created correctly and its implications must be fully understood. Agents should be able to explain the basics and know when to refer clients to an attorney or CPA.', 1),

('ui-3-2', v_mod3, 'How Joint Tenancies Are Severed', E'# How Joint Tenancies Are Severed\n\nA joint tenancy can be **severed** (broken), which converts it into a tenancy in common and eliminates the right of survivorship. Understanding how this happens — both intentionally and accidentally — is critical.\n\n## Voluntary Severance\n\n### Sale or Transfer\nIf one joint tenant sells or transfers their interest to a third party, the joint tenancy is immediately severed as to that share.\n\n**Example:** Alice and Bob are joint tenants. Alice sells her 50% to Carol. Now Bob and Carol are **tenants in common** — not joint tenants. Carol does not have right of survivorship with Bob.\n\n### Conveyance to Self\nIn many states, a joint tenant can sever the joint tenancy by conveying their interest to themselves as a tenant in common. This is sometimes done for estate planning purposes.\n\n### Mutual Agreement\nAll joint tenants can agree in writing to convert their joint tenancy to a tenancy in common.\n\n## Involuntary Severance\n\n### Mortgage or Lien (Varies by State)\nThis is where state law makes a huge difference:\n\n- **Title theory states:** A mortgage transfers title to the lender, which severs the joint tenancy\n- **Lien theory states:** A mortgage is just a lien and does **not** sever the joint tenancy\n\nMost states follow lien theory, meaning a mortgage by one joint tenant does not automatically sever. But this is a complex area — always check your state''s law.\n\n### Divorce\nDivorce proceedings typically sever any joint tenancy between the former spouses, converting it to tenancy in common. The divorce decree or settlement agreement will specify how the property is to be divided.\n\n### Bankruptcy\nIf one joint tenant files for bankruptcy, the bankruptcy trustee may have the power to sell the debtor''s interest, which could sever the joint tenancy.\n\n### Judgment Lien\nA judgment creditor who forces a sale of one joint tenant''s interest severs the joint tenancy for that share.\n\n## Three or More Joint Tenants\n\nSeverance gets more complex with three or more owners:\n\n**Example:** Alice, Bob, and Carol are joint tenants (one-third each). Alice sells her share to Dan.\n\n- Dan holds a one-third interest as a **tenant in common**\n- Bob and Carol remain **joint tenants** with each other for the remaining two-thirds\n- If Bob dies, Carol inherits Bob''s share (survivorship still applies between them)\n- Dan''s share passes to his heirs (no survivorship with Bob or Carol)\n\n## Secret Severance: A Hidden Danger\n\nOne of the biggest risks of joint tenancy is **secret severance**. A joint tenant can sever the joint tenancy by recording a deed conveying their interest — and may not tell the other joint tenant.\n\n**Example:** Alice and Bob are joint tenants. Without telling Bob, Alice records a deed conveying her interest to herself as a tenant in common. When Alice later dies, Bob assumes he''ll inherit Alice''s share through survivorship. But the joint tenancy was already severed — Alice''s share goes to her estate.\n\nThis scenario has led to significant litigation and is one reason some states have enacted notification requirements for severance.\n\n## Agent Implications\n\nWhen working with joint tenancy properties, agents should:\n\n1. **Verify** the current ownership status — has the joint tenancy been severed?\n2. **Check for recorded deeds** that may have converted the ownership\n3. **Ask about divorces, bankruptcies, or transfers** that could have affected the joint tenancy\n4. **Review the title report** carefully for any break in the chain of title\n\n## Summary\n\nJoint tenancy severance can happen intentionally or accidentally, and the consequences are significant. Agents must understand how severance works to protect their clients and ensure transactions proceed smoothly.', 2),

('ui-3-3', v_mod3, 'Joint Tenancy vs. Community Property: Key Differences', E'# Joint Tenancy vs. Community Property: Key Differences\n\nIn community property states, married couples face an important choice: hold property as joint tenants or as community property. Understanding the differences helps agents guide their clients to make informed decisions.\n\n## Side-by-Side Comparison\n\n### Creation\n- **Joint Tenancy:** Must be explicitly stated in the deed with proper language\n- **Community Property:** Automatically applies to property acquired during marriage (in CP states)\n\n### Ownership Split\n- **Joint Tenancy:** Always equal shares\n- **Community Property:** Always 50/50 between spouses\n\n### Right of Survivorship\n- **Joint Tenancy:** Yes — automatic transfer to surviving tenant\n- **Community Property:** Not automatically, unless \"with right of survivorship\" is specified\n\n### Estate Planning Flexibility\n- **Joint Tenancy:** Neither owner can will their share to anyone else\n- **Community Property (without ROS):** Each spouse can will their 50% to anyone\n\n### Tax Treatment at Death\n- **Joint Tenancy:** Only the deceased''s half gets a stepped-up tax basis\n- **Community Property:** **Both halves** get a stepped-up tax basis — this is a major tax advantage\n\n## The Stepped-Up Basis Advantage\n\nThis tax difference alone can be worth hundreds of thousands of dollars:\n\n**Example:** Married couple bought their home in 1990 for $100,000. It''s now worth $800,000. One spouse dies.\n\n**If held as Joint Tenancy:**\n- Surviving spouse''s basis: $50,000 (original half) + $400,000 (deceased''s stepped-up half) = **$450,000**\n- If sold for $800,000, taxable gain = **$350,000**\n\n**If held as Community Property:**\n- Surviving spouse''s basis: $400,000 (stepped-up) + $400,000 (stepped-up) = **$800,000**\n- If sold for $800,000, taxable gain = **$0**\n\nThis is why many estate planning attorneys in community property states recommend holding property as community property rather than joint tenancy.\n\n## Community Property with Right of Survivorship\n\nSeveral community property states now offer a hybrid option: **community property with right of survivorship (CPWROS)**. This provides:\n\n- The **automatic transfer** at death (like joint tenancy)\n- The **full stepped-up basis** tax advantage (like community property)\n- The best of both worlds for many married couples\n\nAvailable in: Arizona, California, Idaho, Nevada, New Mexico, Texas, Washington, Wisconsin\n\n## When to Use Each\n\n**Joint Tenancy may be better when:**\n- Owners are not married to each other\n- Simplicity of survivorship is the primary goal\n- The property has not appreciated significantly\n\n**Community Property may be better when:**\n- Married couples in CP states with significant appreciation\n- Estate planning flexibility is important\n- Tax optimization is a priority\n\n**CPWROS may be best when:**\n- Married couples want both survivorship and the tax advantages\n- Available in their state\n\n## The Agent''s Role\n\nYou should:\n\n1. **Know whether your state is a community property state**\n2. **Understand the basic differences** so you can discuss them with clients\n3. **Never give tax or legal advice** — refer clients to a CPA or attorney\n4. **Recognize when the choice matters** (especially for high-value properties with significant appreciation)\n5. **Ask the right questions** at listing: \"How do you hold title? Have you consulted with an attorney about the best way to hold title?\"\n\n## Summary\n\nThe choice between joint tenancy and community property has significant legal and tax implications. In community property states, the stepped-up basis advantage makes community property (or CPWROS) the preferred choice for many married couples. Agents should understand the basics and refer clients to qualified professionals for specific advice.', 3);

-- Module 3 Quiz
INSERT INTO course_quizzes (module_id, question, options, correct_index, sort_order) VALUES
(v_mod3, 'What is the right of survivorship?', '["The right to live in a property for life", "The automatic transfer of a deceased owner''s share to the surviving owners", "The right to refuse a partition action", "The right to inherit property through a will"]', 1, 1),
(v_mod3, 'What happens if one joint tenant sells their share to a third party?', '["Nothing changes", "The joint tenancy is severed and becomes a tenancy in common", "The buyer becomes a joint tenant", "The sale is void"]', 1, 2),
(v_mod3, 'What major tax advantage does community property have over joint tenancy?', '["Community property is exempt from property taxes", "Both halves get a stepped-up basis at death, not just the deceased''s half", "Community property is never subject to capital gains tax", "Community property qualifies for a higher mortgage deduction"]', 1, 3),
(v_mod3, 'Can a joint tenancy be severed without the other joint tenant''s knowledge?', '["No, all joint tenants must consent to severance", "Yes, one joint tenant can record a deed that severs the joint tenancy", "Only a court can sever a joint tenancy", "Severance requires both owners to sign"]', 1, 4),
(v_mod3, 'How many states are community property states?', '["All 50 states", "25 states", "9 states plus optional in a few others", "Only California and Texas"]', 2, 5);


-- =============================================
-- MODULE 4: Title Issues and Transaction Challenges
-- =============================================
INSERT INTO course_modules (title, section, description, tier, sort_order, course_id)
VALUES (
  'Title Issues and Transaction Challenges',
  'Navigating Transactions',
  'Learn to identify and resolve the most common title issues that arise with co-owned properties, from missing signatures to clouded titles and encumbrances.',
  'free',
  4,
  v_course_id
) RETURNING id INTO v_mod4;

INSERT INTO course_lessons (id, module_id, title, content, sort_order) VALUES
('ui-4-1', v_mod4, 'Common Title Problems with Co-Owned Properties', E'# Common Title Problems with Co-Owned Properties\n\nCo-owned properties are more likely to have title issues than single-owner properties. As an agent, recognizing these problems early can save your clients time, money, and heartache.\n\n## 1. Missing or Deceased Co-Owners\n\n**The Problem:** A co-owner has died but their interest was never properly transferred, or a co-owner cannot be located.\n\n**Impact on Transaction:**\n- Cannot sell the full property without all owners (or their legal representatives)\n- Title company will flag this and may refuse to insure\n- May need a court order (quiet title action) to clear the title\n\n**Agent Action:**\n- Order a preliminary title report early\n- Ask sellers about all co-owners and their current status\n- If an owner is deceased, confirm whether probate has been completed\n- If an owner is missing, refer to an attorney immediately\n\n## 2. Unrecorded Interests\n\n**The Problem:** Someone has an ownership interest that is not reflected in the public record. Common examples:\n- Oral agreements to share ownership\n- Written agreements that were never recorded\n- Equitable interests based on financial contributions\n\n**Impact on Transaction:**\n- A claimant may emerge after the sale\n- Title insurance may not cover unrecorded claims\n- Disputes over the true ownership can delay or kill the deal\n\n**Agent Action:**\n- Ask sellers: \"Is there anyone else who claims an interest in this property?\"\n- Review the title report for any gaps in the chain of title\n- Recommend title insurance for buyers (and explain what it does and doesn''t cover)\n\n## 3. Liens Against Individual Co-Owners\n\n**The Problem:** One co-owner has a judgment, tax lien, or other encumbrance against their individual interest.\n\n**Impact on Transaction:**\n- The lien must be satisfied or negotiated as part of the sale\n- May reduce the net proceeds to that co-owner\n- In some cases, can prevent the sale from closing\n\n**Agent Action:**\n- Review the title report for liens against each individual owner\n- Ensure the closing agent addresses all liens in the settlement\n- If a lien exceeds the owner''s share of proceeds, creative solutions may be needed\n\n## 4. Divorce-Related Complications\n\n**The Problem:** A married couple is selling property during or after a divorce, and the divorce decree''s property division doesn''t match the deed.\n\n**Impact on Transaction:**\n- The deed may still show both spouses, even if one was awarded the property\n- A quitclaim deed may be needed from the non-owning ex-spouse\n- The title company needs proof of the divorce decree''s terms\n\n**Agent Action:**\n- Ask: \"Has this property been addressed in a divorce settlement?\"\n- Request a copy of the relevant divorce decree provisions\n- Coordinate with both parties'' attorneys if needed\n\n## 5. Inconsistent Vesting\n\n**The Problem:** The way title is held (vesting) has changed over time through various deeds, and the records don''t tell a clear story.\n\n**Example:** Original deed says \"Alice and Bob as joint tenants.\" Later, a refinance deed says \"Alice and Bob.\" Does this mean the joint tenancy was severed?\n\n**Impact on Transaction:**\n- Uncertainty about the current form of ownership\n- May affect who needs to sign documents\n- Could impact survivorship rights\n\n**Agent Action:**\n- Review all deeds in the chain of title, not just the most recent one\n- Ensure the current vesting is clearly established before marketing\n- Recommend a title attorney review complex vesting histories\n\n## 6. Fraud and Forgery\n\n**The Problem:** A deed or signature is forged, or one co-owner transfers the property without the other''s knowledge or consent.\n\n**Impact on Transaction:**\n- The fraudulent transfer is void (it never legally happened)\n- An innocent buyer could lose the property — unless protected by title insurance\n- Criminal liability for the forger\n\n**Agent Action:**\n- Verify seller identities carefully\n- Watch for red flags: rushed timelines, absent co-owners, unusual circumstances\n- Ensure proper notarization of all documents\n\n## Prevention Is Key\n\nThe best way to handle title problems is to **prevent them** by:\n\n1. Ordering title searches early in the process\n2. Asking thorough questions about ownership history\n3. Ensuring all owners are involved from the start\n4. Working with experienced title companies and attorneys\n5. Getting title insurance for every transaction\n\n## Summary\n\nTitle issues with co-owned properties are common and can range from easily resolved to extremely complex. Agents who know what to look for and act proactively can keep transactions on track and protect their clients.', 1),

('ui-4-2', v_mod4, 'Financing Co-Owned Properties', E'# Financing Co-Owned Properties\n\nFinancing is one of the biggest practical challenges with co-owned properties. Understanding how lenders view these transactions helps agents set realistic expectations and structure deals that can actually close.\n\n## How Lenders View Co-Ownership\n\nLenders want certainty: they want to know exactly what they''re lending against and who is responsible for repayment. Co-ownership introduces uncertainty that lenders try to manage through:\n\n- **Requiring all owners on the mortgage** — most common approach\n- **Higher interest rates** or more conservative underwriting\n- **Requiring a TIC or co-ownership agreement** as a loan condition\n- **Declining to lend** on properties with complex ownership structures\n\n## Common Financing Scenarios\n\n### Scenario 1: All Co-Owners on One Mortgage\n\nThe most straightforward approach:\n- All co-owners are co-borrowers on a single mortgage\n- All co-owners'' credit scores, income, and DTI ratios are evaluated\n- **The weakest borrower''s credit** can affect the rate and approval\n- All co-owners are **jointly and severally liable** — each is responsible for the full payment\n\n**Agent tip:** If one co-owner has poor credit, it may be better for the other owners to qualify alone (if they can) and use a different ownership structure.\n\n### Scenario 2: Fractional TIC Loans\n\nIn some markets, individual co-owners can get separate mortgages on their undivided interest:\n\n- Each owner borrows against only their share\n- If one owner defaults, only their share is at risk (in theory)\n- **Very limited availability** — primarily in San Francisco and a few other markets\n- Higher rates and stricter qualifying requirements\n- Requires a comprehensive TIC agreement\n\n### Scenario 3: One Owner Finances, Others Pay Cash\n\nSometimes not all co-owners need financing:\n- Only the borrowing owner(s) are on the mortgage\n- Non-borrowing owners may still need to sign the deed of trust\n- The mortgage creates a lien on the **entire property**, not just the borrower''s share\n- This puts the cash-paying owners at risk if the borrower defaults\n\n### Scenario 4: Refinancing with Multiple Owners\n\nRefinancing a co-owned property adds complexity:\n- All owners typically must consent and sign\n- If one owner refuses, refinancing may not be possible\n- Change in terms affects all owners\n- May trigger reevaluation of the TIC agreement\n\n## The DTI Challenge\n\nDebt-to-income (DTI) ratio calculations for co-owned properties can be tricky:\n\n- If all owners are on the mortgage, the **full mortgage payment** affects each owner''s DTI\n- Some lenders will allocate the payment proportionally (e.g., 50% for a 50% owner)\n- Others will count the full payment against each borrower\n- This can prevent co-owners from qualifying for other loans\n\n**Agent tip:** Have clients discuss DTI implications with their lender before committing to a co-ownership purchase.\n\n## Special Considerations\n\n### Investment Properties\n- Higher down payment requirements (typically 20-25%)\n- Higher interest rates\n- Rental income from the property may help with qualification\n- Lender may require the property to be held in an LLC (which changes the ownership structure)\n\n### Construction Loans\n- Even more complex with multiple owners\n- All owners must agree on plans, budgets, and timelines\n- Lender may require one designated borrower/decision-maker\n\n### USDA/VA/FHA Loans\n- These government-backed loans have specific rules about co-borrowers\n- VA loans require the veteran to occupy the property\n- FHA loans have specific guidelines for non-occupant co-borrowers\n- USDA loans are for primary residences in eligible areas only\n\n## Summary\n\nFinancing co-owned properties requires careful planning and clear communication among all owners. Agents should understand the lending landscape, set realistic expectations with clients, and connect them with lenders experienced in these transactions.', 2),

('ui-4-3', v_mod4, 'Partition Actions: When Co-Owners Disagree', E'# Partition Actions: When Co-Owners Disagree\n\nWhen co-owners cannot agree on what to do with a shared property, the legal remedy is a **partition action**. As an agent, understanding partition is essential because it directly impacts your ability to list and sell co-owned properties.\n\n## What Is Partition?\n\nPartition is a legal proceeding that allows any co-owner to force the division or sale of co-owned property. There are two types:\n\n### Partition in Kind (Physical Division)\n- The property is physically divided into separate parcels\n- Each co-owner gets their own separate parcel\n- Works well for large, unimproved land\n- **Rarely practical** for houses, condos, or commercial buildings\n- Courts prefer this method if feasible because it preserves the property\n\n### Partition by Sale (Forced Sale)\n- The property is sold and the proceeds are divided among the owners\n- Used when physical division is impractical or would significantly reduce value\n- This is the **most common outcome** for residential properties\n- The sale is usually conducted by a court-appointed referee or commissioner\n\n## The Partition Process\n\n1. **Filing:** One or more co-owners file a partition complaint with the court\n2. **Service:** All other co-owners must be served with the lawsuit\n3. **Accounting:** The court may order an accounting of expenses, contributions, and profits\n4. **Determination:** The court decides whether partition in kind or by sale is appropriate\n5. **Execution:** The property is divided or sold, and proceeds are distributed\n\n## Timeline and Costs\n\n- A partition action can take **6 months to 2+ years**\n- Legal fees can run **$10,000 to $50,000 or more** per party\n- Court-ordered sales often result in **below-market prices** (10-30% less)\n- The costs of partition are typically deducted from the sale proceeds before distribution\n\n## Financial Adjustments in Partition\n\nThe court will consider each owner''s contributions when dividing proceeds:\n\n- **Mortgage payments:** An owner who paid more than their share may be credited\n- **Property taxes:** Same — disproportionate payments are adjusted\n- **Improvements:** An owner who made improvements may be compensated (but not always at full cost)\n- **Rent:** An owner who occupied the property may owe rent to non-occupying owners\n- **Damage:** An owner who damaged or neglected the property may be charged\n\n## Alternatives to Partition\n\nBefore litigation, agents should encourage co-owners to consider:\n\n### Negotiated Buyout\nOne owner buys out the other(s) at an agreed-upon price. This is usually the best outcome for everyone.\n\n### Mediation\nA neutral mediator helps the owners reach an agreement. Faster, cheaper, and less adversarial than litigation.\n\n### Private Sale\nThe owners agree to sell on the open market and split the proceeds. This almost always results in a higher price than a court-ordered sale.\n\n### Listing Agreement with Contingencies\nAll owners sign a listing agreement with agreed-upon terms (minimum price, timeline, etc.).\n\n## Agent''s Role in Partition Situations\n\n### When You''re Contacted by One Co-Owner\n- Listen to their situation and understand the ownership structure\n- Explain the realities of selling an undivided interest vs. the whole property\n- Recommend mediation or negotiation before litigation\n- If they insist on listing only their interest, be honest about the challenges\n\n### When You''re Appointed by the Court\n- Some courts appoint real estate agents or referees to handle partition sales\n- You must be impartial and represent the interests of all parties\n- Follow the court''s instructions precisely\n- Document everything\n\n### When You''re Listing After a Partition Agreement\n- Ensure you have written authorization from all necessary parties\n- Understand any terms or conditions imposed by the court or agreement\n- Price the property fairly — this is not the time for aggressive pricing\n- Be transparent with buyers about the ownership situation\n\n## Summary\n\nPartition actions are the legal last resort when co-owners cannot agree. They''re expensive, time-consuming, and usually result in below-market prices. Agents who understand partition can help clients avoid it by facilitating negotiation and presenting alternatives. When partition is unavoidable, agents who understand the process can help minimize the damage.', 3);

