(v_mod4, 'What is the most common type of partition for residential properties?', '["Partition in kind", "Partition by sale", "Partition by agreement", "Partition by deed"]', 1, 1),
(v_mod4, 'When one co-owner has a judgment lien, what impact can it have on a sale?', '["No impact at all", "The lien must be satisfied or negotiated as part of the sale", "The sale is automatically void", "The other owners must pay the lien"]', 1, 2),
(v_mod4, 'Why might a lender require all co-owners to be on the mortgage?', '["Because it is required by federal law", "To ensure all owners are jointly and severally liable for repayment", "Because it reduces the interest rate", "To avoid paying property taxes"]', 1, 3),
(v_mod4, 'What is the best alternative to a partition action for most co-owners?', '["Filing for bankruptcy", "A negotiated buyout or private sale", "Abandoning the property", "Refinancing the mortgage"]', 1, 4),
(v_mod4, 'Court-ordered partition sales typically result in what?', '["Above-market prices due to competition", "Below-market prices, often 10-30% less", "Exactly market value", "No sale, just property division"]', 1, 5);


-- =============================================
-- MODULE 5: Special Situations for Agents
-- =============================================
INSERT INTO course_modules (title, section, description, tier, sort_order, course_id)
VALUES (
  'Special Situations for Agents',
  'Navigating Transactions',
  'Handle the trickiest co-ownership scenarios including inheritance, divorce, investment groups, and working with attorneys and courts.',
  'free',
  5,
  v_course_id
) RETURNING id INTO v_mod5;

INSERT INTO course_lessons (id, module_id, title, content, sort_order) VALUES
('ui-5-1', v_mod5, 'Inherited Properties and Heirs'' Property', E'# Inherited Properties and Heirs'' Property\n\nOne of the most common — and emotionally charged — co-ownership situations agents encounter is inherited property. When a property owner dies, their interest may be split among multiple heirs, creating a co-ownership arrangement that none of them chose.\n\n## How Property Is Inherited\n\n### With a Will (Testate)\n- The will specifies who receives the property\n- Must go through **probate** to transfer title\n- May create tenancy in common among multiple beneficiaries\n- Executor handles the property during probate\n\n### Without a Will (Intestate)\n- State **intestacy laws** determine who inherits\n- Typically, the property goes to the closest surviving relatives\n- Can result in many co-owners (especially after multiple generations)\n- This is the primary cause of **heirs'' property**\n\n### Through Joint Tenancy\n- Property passes automatically to the surviving joint tenant\n- No probate needed — just a death certificate and affidavit\n- The simplest transfer, but not always the best tax strategy\n\n### Through a Trust\n- Property held in a revocable living trust passes according to the trust terms\n- Avoids probate entirely\n- The successor trustee handles the transfer\n\n## The Heirs'' Property Crisis\n\nHeirs'' property is a nationwide problem that disproportionately affects rural and minority communities:\n\n**What it is:** Property passed down through generations without wills or formal probate, resulting in dozens or even hundreds of co-owners — many of whom may not know each other or even know they have an interest.\n\n**Why it matters:**\n- Heirs'' property owners often cannot get mortgages, home equity loans, or FEMA assistance\n- Any single co-owner can file a partition action and force a sale\n- Developers and speculators sometimes buy one heir''s small interest and then force a sale of the entire property\n- An estimated **$28 billion** in Black-owned land has been lost through heirs'' property issues\n\n## The Uniform Partition of Heirs Property Act (UPHPA)\n\nMany states have adopted the UPHPA to protect heirs'' property owners:\n\n- Requires **court-ordered appraisals** before partition sales\n- Gives co-owners the **right to buy** the petitioning owner''s share\n- Requires the court to consider a **sale on the open market** rather than a forced auction\n- Provides more protections against predatory partition actions\n\n## Agent Best Practices for Inherited Properties\n\n### At Listing\n1. **Identify all owners** — run a title search and trace the chain of ownership\n2. **Determine the type of co-ownership** — was there a will? Probate? Joint tenancy?\n3. **Get written authorization** from all owners or their legal representatives\n4. **Understand the emotional dynamics** — inherited property sales are often deeply personal\n5. **Check for outstanding liens** against the estate or individual heirs\n\n### During the Transaction\n1. **Communicate with all owners** — even those who are not the primary contact\n2. **Be patient** — decision-making with multiple heirs takes longer\n3. **Watch for disputes** among heirs and address them early\n4. **Ensure probate is complete** before listing (or know the timeline)\n5. **Coordinate with the estate attorney** on title and closing issues\n\n### When an Heir Wants to Sell but Others Don''t\n1. Explore a **buyout** by the other heirs\n2. Suggest **mediation** to reach agreement\n3. Explain the cost and risk of **partition actions**\n4. If the heir insists on selling their interest alone, be transparent about the limited market\n\n## Summary\n\nInherited properties represent both a significant opportunity and a significant challenge for agents. Understanding how inheritance creates co-ownership, knowing the legal protections available, and handling these emotionally sensitive transactions with care will make you an invaluable resource for your clients.', 1),

('ui-5-2', v_mod5, 'Divorce and Co-Owned Property', E'# Divorce and Co-Owned Property\n\nDivorce is one of the most common triggers for co-owned property transactions. Agents who understand the legal and emotional dimensions of these situations can provide exceptional service during a difficult time.\n\n## How Divorce Affects Property Ownership\n\n### Community Property States\n- Property acquired during marriage is presumed 50/50\n- Separate property (pre-marriage, gifts, inheritance) remains separate\n- The court divides community property equitably (usually 50/50)\n\n### Equitable Distribution States\n- Courts divide property \"equitably\" — which doesn''t always mean equally\n- Factors include length of marriage, income, contributions, and future needs\n- Pre-marital property may still be divided if it was commingled\n\n## Common Outcomes for the Family Home\n\n### Option 1: Sell and Split Proceeds\n- Most straightforward approach\n- Both parties agree to list, sell, and divide the net proceeds\n- The divorce decree specifies the split (e.g., 50/50 or other ratio)\n\n### Option 2: One Spouse Buys Out the Other\n- The keeping spouse refinances into their name only\n- The departing spouse receives their share of equity\n- A quitclaim deed transfers the departing spouse''s interest\n- **Critical:** The buyout must be completed — many divorcing spouses assume the decree alone removes them from the mortgage, but it does NOT\n\n### Option 3: Deferred Sale (Bird''s Nest)\n- The property is kept temporarily (often until children reach a certain age)\n- Both spouses remain on the mortgage and deed\n- The divorce decree specifies when and how the property will eventually be sold\n- Creates ongoing co-ownership obligations\n\n### Option 4: One Spouse Gets the House\n- Awarded to one spouse as part of the overall property division\n- The other spouse receives other assets to compensate\n- Same refinancing and quitclaim requirements as a buyout\n\n## Key Issues for Agents\n\n### Who Has Authority to List?\n- If both spouses are on the deed, **both must sign** the listing agreement\n- A divorce decree ordering the sale may give one spouse authority to list\n- If one spouse refuses to sign, a court order may be needed\n- Always get legal clarity before proceeding\n\n### Mortgage vs. Deed\n- The deed shows who **owns** the property\n- The mortgage shows who **owes** on the loan\n- A divorce decree can change who owns the property but **cannot** remove someone from a mortgage\n- Only **refinancing** removes someone from mortgage liability\n\n### Working with Both Parties\n- Ideally, represent one spouse and let the other get their own agent\n- If representing both (with consent), maintain strict impartiality\n- Communicate with both parties and their attorneys\n- Never take sides or share confidential information between parties\n\n### Pricing and Timing\n- Divorcing sellers may have different motivations (one wants a quick sale, the other wants top dollar)\n- Agree on pricing strategy in writing before listing\n- Set a timeline with price reduction triggers if the property doesn''t sell\n- Be prepared for emotional reactions and changing minds\n\n### Financial Complications\n- Outstanding liens, unpaid taxes, or second mortgages\n- One spouse may have damaged credit during the separation\n- Capital gains exclusion rules (both spouses may be able to use the $250K exclusion)\n- Transfer tax exemptions for divorce-related transfers (check your state)\n\n## Communication Tips\n\n1. **Be empathetic** but remain professional\n2. **Don''t play therapist** — recommend counseling resources if needed\n3. **Document everything** in writing and share with both parties\n4. **Stay neutral** in all communications\n5. **Be patient** — decisions take longer during emotional upheaval\n\n## Summary\n\nDivorce-related property transactions require a combination of technical knowledge, legal awareness, and emotional intelligence. Agents who handle these situations well earn referrals for years to come.', 2),

('ui-5-3', v_mod5, 'Working with Attorneys, Courts, and Title Companies', E'# Working with Attorneys, Courts, and Title Companies\n\nCo-ownership transactions frequently involve legal professionals. Knowing how to work effectively with attorneys, courts, and title companies makes the difference between a smooth closing and a deal that falls apart.\n\n## Working with Real Estate Attorneys\n\n### When to Refer to an Attorney\nAlways recommend an attorney when:\n- The co-ownership structure is complex or disputed\n- A partition action is threatened or pending\n- Heirs'' property issues exist\n- The divorce decree is unclear about property division\n- Tax implications are significant (1031 exchanges, capital gains)\n- One or more owners are incapacitated or in a trust\n- Title defects require legal action to resolve\n\n### How to Work with Attorneys Effectively\n\n**Do:**\n- Provide clear, factual information about the property and transaction\n- Share copies of deeds, title reports, and relevant documents\n- Respect the attorney-client relationship — communicate through the attorney when asked\n- Ask for written confirmation of any instructions that affect the transaction\n- Keep a record of all communications\n\n**Don''t:**\n- Give legal advice or interpret legal documents for clients\n- Interfere with attorney-client communications\n- Pressure attorneys to speed up legal processes\n- Share confidential information from one party''s attorney with the other party\n\n## Working with Title Companies\n\n### Why Title Companies Matter\nTitle companies play a crucial role in co-ownership transactions by:\n- **Searching** the chain of title for all owners and encumbrances\n- **Identifying** any issues that need to be resolved before closing\n- **Insuring** the buyer against title defects\n- **Facilitating** the closing and ensuring all documents are properly executed\n\n### Best Practices\n\n1. **Order title early** — co-owned properties are more likely to have issues that take time to resolve\n2. **Request a preliminary title report** and review it carefully\n3. **Ask questions** about anything you don''t understand\n4. **Flag issues proactively** — share what you know about the ownership history\n5. **Ensure all owners** are accounted for in the title search\n\n### Common Title Requirements for Co-Ownership Sales\n- Signatures from all owners (or their legal representatives)\n- Death certificates for deceased co-owners\n- Probate documents (letters testamentary, court orders)\n- Divorce decrees affecting property\n- Powers of attorney (if an owner cannot sign in person)\n- Court orders (for partition sales or disputed ownership)\n\n## Working with Courts\n\n### When Courts Are Involved\n- **Probate:** Transferring title from a deceased owner\n- **Partition:** Court-ordered division or sale\n- **Guardianship:** When an owner is incapacitated\n- **Quiet title:** Resolving disputes about ownership\n- **Bankruptcy:** When an owner''s bankruptcy affects the property\n\n### The Agent''s Role in Court-Involved Transactions\n\n1. **Follow the court''s instructions** precisely\n2. **Get everything in writing** — verbal approvals from attorneys are not enough\n3. **Don''t sign anything** you don''t understand\n4. **Meet deadlines** — court timelines are strict\n5. **Keep detailed records** of all activities, showings, and offers\n\n### Court-Ordered Sales\nIf appointed to sell a property by court order:\n- You represent the **court''s interests** (fairness to all parties), not any single owner\n- Pricing should reflect fair market value — get an appraisal\n- Marketing should be thorough and well-documented\n- All offers must be presented to the court or the appointed referee\n- The court must approve the final sale\n\n## Building Your Professional Network\n\nAs an agent handling co-ownership properties, you should build relationships with:\n\n- **Real estate attorneys** who specialize in co-ownership, partition, and estate matters\n- **Probate attorneys** for inherited property transactions\n- **Family law attorneys** for divorce-related sales\n- **Title officers** who are experienced with complex ownership structures\n- **CPAs** who understand the tax implications of co-ownership transactions\n- **Mediators** who can help resolve co-owner disputes\n\nHaving these professionals on speed dial positions you as the go-to agent for co-ownership transactions in your market.\n\n## Summary\n\nSuccessful co-ownership transactions require collaboration with legal and title professionals. Agents who know when to bring in specialists, how to work with them effectively, and how to navigate court-involved transactions will close more deals and better serve their clients.', 3);

